		<p>The phrase death certificate can refer either to a document issued by a medical practitioner certifying the deceased state of a person or, popularly, to a document issued by a person such as a registrar of vital statistics that declares the date, location and cause of a person's death as later entered in an official register of deaths.</p>

		<p>A full explanation of the cause of death includes four items:</p>
            	<ul>
            		<li>The immediate cause of death, such as the heart stopping.</li>
                    <li>The intermediate causes, which triggered the immediate cause, such as a myocardial infarction.</li>
                    <li>The underlying causes, which triggered the chain of events leading to death, such as atherosclerosis.</li>
                    <li>Any other diseases and disorders the person had at the time of death, even though they did not directly cause the death.</li>
                </ul>

		<h2>Required Documents</h2>
		<ul>
			<li>Original Death Certificate issued by the relevant Authorities.</li>
            <li>Coroner’s Report</li>
            <li>Passport and other available identification documents of the deceased, to prove Sri Lankan Citizenship.</li>
		</ul>

		<h2>Required Information</h2>
		<ul>
			<li>Date  and  place  of  death</li>
            <li>Full  name  and  residence </li>
            <li>Sex</li>
            <li>Age </li>
            <li>Rank  or  profession</li>
            <li>Parents’  full  names</li>
            <li>Registrars Division</li>
            <li>Cause  of  death  and  place  of  burial  orcremation</li>
            <li>Declarant's information</li>
		</ul>

